---
name: scljet-index-mutate
description: SclJet index-maintaining delete — deleting a table row also updates its index, so integrity_check still passes (cross-backend)
backends: [int, js]
---

# SclJet index-maintaining mutate

[ByteSlice, byteSliceToList, SqliteValue, SqlInteger, SqlText, buildTableWithIndexDatabase](std/scljet/index.ssc)
[deleteRowidsIndexed](std/scljet/mutate.ssc)

```scalascript
// Build a table with an index on `n`, then delete rowid 3 (n=20). The table AND the
// index are rebuilt from the surviving rows, so reference integrity_check (which
// cross-checks the index against the table) still passes and the index no longer
// references the deleted row. int and JS agree.
val rows = List(
  List(SqlInteger(30L), SqlText("thirty")),
  List(SqlInteger(10L), SqlText("ten")),
  List(SqlInteger(20L), SqlText("twenty")),
  List(SqlInteger(5L), SqlText("five")),
  List(SqlInteger(25L), SqlText("twentyfive")))

buildTableWithIndexDatabase(512, 1, 1, "t", "CREATE TABLE t(n INTEGER, v TEXT)",
  "idx", "CREATE INDEX idx ON t(n)", List(0), rows) match
  case Right(db) =>
    deleteRowidsIndexed(db, 2, 1, List(0), List(3L)) match
      case Right(newDb) => println((newDb.length / 512).toString + ":" + byteSliceToList(newDb).toString)
      case Left(message) => println("MUTATE-ERROR:" + message)
  case Left(error) => println("BUILD-ERROR:" + error.message)
```
